x4freetext: Spallation reaction induced by 20 GeV/c protons
from CERN Proton Synchrotron in massive lead target.
High intensity of 7.E12 protons/pulse results in very
high instantaneous neutron flux in energy region
1 eV - 250 MeV. 5.8 cm thick layer around the lead
spallation target as coolant and moderator, yielding a
wide energy spectrum from thermal to 250 MeV.
Evacuated neutron path of 185 m distance from target.
Two collimators at 137 and 175 m, - layers of iron and
borated polyethylene.Sweeping magnet at 145 m distance
Nominal repetition rate of pulsed beam 2.4 sec, low
enough to cover the TOF range down to subthermal
energies and to prevent overlapping of slow neutrons
1.9 cm diameter collimator beam spot, instantaneous
flux amounts to 10**5 n/cm**2/pulse for neutron
Neutron flux was measured by silicon monitor (see

deposition on thin Mylar foil surrounded by set of four
silicon detectors outside the neutron beam for
recording  the tritons and alpha particles from
Neutron energy was determined by time of flight
The relationship for converting TOF into neutron energy
was verified in energy range from 1 eV to about 1 MeV
by means of specific capture resonances in S-32,Ir-193,
Total energy detection system with two C6D6
efficiency fro capture gamma-ray cascades and energy
resolution of 15 % at 662 keV and 6% at 6.1 MeV.
Consist of 40 BaF2 crystals contained in B-10 loaded
carbon fibre capsules forming a spherical shell of 15cm

layer, which moderates and absorbers sample scattered
neutrons. Energy calibration of each individual BaF2
crystal was obtained by means of standard gamma-ray

Neutron sensitivity of C6D6 setup about 1.E-4, two
Silicon flux monitor (SiMon) consisted of thin

U-235 parallel plate fission ionization chamber
of PTB Braunschweig, Germany, to measure the relative

For dead-time introduced by calorimetric method < 5%.
